"Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Territoire du Bassin de la Sarre, Allemagne":"Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","Erfweiler-Ehlingen, Mandelbachtal, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany":"Erfweiler-Ehlingen, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Deutschland":"Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Schwarz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Otto, Erwin, Gunter, Heinz, Wolfgang, Gerhard, Manfred, Klaus, Bernhard, Ernst.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Schwartz  . This surname is also found in Slovakia, Czechia, Poland, Croatia, and Slovenia, where it is more common in Slavicized forms (see 2 below) and where it was often applied as a translation into German of Slavic cognates like Czech and Slovak <b>Černý</b> (see   Cerny   1), Slovenian <b>Černe</b> (see   Cerne   1). It is also found in some western European countries, notably in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and the Netherlands.","Germanized form of Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian <b>Švarc</b> (see   Swartz   2) and Polish   Szwarc  , surnames of German origin (see above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Szwarc","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Zofia, Brunon, Dariusz, Janina, Janusz, Mariusz, Pawel, Waclaw, Zbigniew.","Polish: from German   Schwarz   or   Schwartz  ."]},{"name":"Swartzel","meanings":["Americanized form of South German <b>Schwärzel</b>, a diminutive of   Schwarz  ."]},{"name":"Schwarzmann","meanings":["German: variant of   Schwarz   ‘dark, black’, with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): descriptive nickname for a dark-skinned or black-haired man, from German <i>schwarz</i> ‘black’ + <i>Mann</i> ‘man’. Compare   Schwartzman  ,   Schwarzman  , and   Shvartsman  ."]},{"name":"Swatzell","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of German <b>Schwärzel</b>, <b>Schwerzel</b>, a nickname from a diminutive of   Schwarz  , or of German <b>Schwetzel</b>, of uncertain origin."]},{"name":"Schwartz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Emanuel, Meyer, Chaim, Isadore, Moshe, Aron, Ari, Mayer, Hershel.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for someone with black hair or a dark complexion, from Middle High German <i>swarz</i>, German <i>schwarz</i>, Yiddish <i>shvarts</i> ‘dark, black’. In some cases this may be a habitational name from any of the places called Schwarz, named with the same word. This form of the surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Denmark, Sweden, Hungary, etc. Compare   Schwarcz  ,   Schwarz  ,   Shwartz  ,   Swarts  , and   Swartz  ."]}]},{"name":"Agathe","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Agatha</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agathe Schwarz was born about 1500, in Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany as the daughter of Jean Schwartz and Epse. She married Johann Landorff about 1525, in Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"environ 1500–":"umbes 1500–Surnud","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1470–1553":"1470–1553","1520–1597":"1520–1597","1520–1607":"1520–1607","1479–1530":"1479–1530","–Female":"Surnud","environ 1500":"umbes 1500","1479":"1479","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1597":"1597","1553":"1553","1530":"1530","1607":"1607","1470":"1470","um 1525":"umbes 1525","Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Alemanha":"Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Saksamaa","Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Territoire du Bassin de la Sarre, Allemagne":"Erfweile